            @Html.ActionLink("Reviews", "Index", "Reviews", new { id=item.Id },null) |      @* <== Click "Reviews: to navigate to the new Review's Controller Index View. *@
            @Html.ActionLink("Delete", "Delete", new { id=item.Id })

            @*This is wrong (i.e. without the 'null' parm : @Html.ActionLink("Reviews", "Index", "Reviews", new { id=item.Id })
                For the 'ActionLink' this is using overload 5 of 10, and The id is going to an 'object' htmlAttributes in this overload, and it is preceeded by "Reviews" which is an object routeValues.
                The way you can tell is execute the code, go to the link on the page and hover over it, if you see something like this, with a "Length=" then it is wrong:
                "http://localhost:12345/Restaurant?Length=7"
                With the correct signature of parms (overload 7 of 10), "Reviews" is the controller name,  the 'new { id=item.Id }' is going to the 'object' routeValues parameter, and the 'null' is going to to the 'object' htmlAttributes
                Now when you hover over the link you will see this: "http://localhost:12345/Reviews/Index/1"



            NOTE the use of 'id' is ambigous.
            We could write: new { restaurantID = item.id}
            Which would yield the following URL: /Reviews/Index?restaurantID=3


            NOTE: Could add a new Route
                    routes.MapRoute(
                                     "Reviews",
                                     "Reviews/{action}/{restaurantId},
                                     new { controller="Reviews"});

            *@
        </td>
    </tr>
}

</table>

